{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}
{% set nav = 'about' %}

{% block title %}About this resource · Robinson Huron Treaty{% endblock %}
{% block description %}What this Robinson Huron Treaty resource is, and is not: member-led, not the Litigation Fund. How to correct a community page, how to make contact, and how OIATC helped start it.{% endblock %}
{% block og_description %}What the Robinson Huron Treaty resource hub is and is not, how to correct a community page, and how to make contact.{% endblock %}

{% block hero %}
<section class="hero">
  <div class="wrap wrap--wide">
    <p class="eyebrow">About this resource</p>
    <h1>About this resource.</h1>
    <p class="lead">This is a broad, member-led resource for the Robinson Huron Treaty and its 21 First Nations: what the treaty is, who the communities are, what is happening on the land, and the member-led transparency work on the shared settlement.</p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <h2>What this is, and is not</h2>
  <div class="card card--magenta">
    <ul>
      <li>Members and beneficiaries of the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations build and run it.</li>
      <li>It is not the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund, a band council, a council committee, or any community's administration.</li>
      <li>It is about member information and transparency, not about removing or attacking any leader.</li>
      <li>It works from sourced facts framed as questions. It does not make accusations, and it names no private individuals in the pages it writes in its own voice.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p>The member-led part of this resource is <a href="/circle">the Transparency Circle</a>. The rest, the <a href="/treaty">treaty orientation</a>, the <a href="/communities">community pages</a>, and the <a href="/land">land section</a>, is a neutral resource open to anyone in or asking about the territory: members, neighbours, students, and journalists.</p>

  <h2 id="corrections">Corrections</h2>
  <p>The community pages are member-compiled summaries drawn from public sources. They are not official communications of any nation, and they are independent of each nation's Chief and Council. Getting a nation's name, governance, or numbers wrong is worse than not having the page, so corrections matter to us.</p>
  <p>If you see something on a community page, or anywhere on this site, that is wrong or out of date, please tell us and we will fix it. We prefer each nation's own website and the federal CIRNAC and ISC First Nation Profiles registry as the authorities for governance and population, and we treat all of that as point-in-time, so we re-verify before relying on it.</p>
  <div class="card card--coral">
    <h3>How to send a correction</h3>
    <p>Tell us the page, the detail that is wrong, and, where you can, a public source we can check (for example, the nation's own site). We will correct the page and, on the community pages, the underlying summary.</p>
    <p class="muted">Send the correction through the <a href="/contact">contact form</a>, or share it with a Circle local contact in your community.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>If you are a beneficiary of a Robinson Huron Treaty First Nation and you want your community represented, or you want to send a correction, use the <a href="/contact">contact form</a> and a member will reply. You can also <a href="/get-involved">get involved</a>.</p>

  <h2>Our relationship to OIATC</h2>
  <p>OIATC helped start this resource. Members run it, not OIATC.</p>
{% endblock %}
